    <p><input id="q1" type="droptarget"/><br/>This pattern is true for almost all other equipment.</p>
 
   <p><input id="q2" type="droptarget"/><br/>For example, the percentage of boys with computers in their bedroom is almost twice the percentage for girls.</p>
	  
  <p><input id="q3" type="droptarget"/><br/>Almost 1 in 2 children have one.</p>
  
  <p><input id="q4" type="droptarget"/><br/>It is clear that a large proportion of all children, just over 50 per cent, have some kind of equipment in their bedroom and that the percentage is considerably higher for boys.</p>
	  
   <p><input id="q5" type="droptarget"/><br/>The television is closely followed by games consoles in popularity.</p>
	 
   <p><input id="q6" type="droptarget"/><br/>The only exception is video cassette recorders, which are slightly more common in girls' bedrooms.</p>
	 
  <p><input id="q7" type="droptarget"/><br/>A third of boys own such consoles compared to only a fifth of girls.</p>
  
    <p><input id="q8" type="droptarget"/><br/>A closer look at the figures shows that the most common appliance found in children's bedrooms is the television set.</p>
  
  <p><input id="q9" type="droptarget"/><br/>However, these are far more popular with boys than with girls.</p>
  
  <p><input id="q10" type="droptarget"/><br/>The bar chart shows the percentages of girls and boys with home entertainment equipment in their bedrooms.</p>
  
  <p><input id="q11" type="droptarget"/><br/>We might also wonder what effect this has on their social development.</p>
  
  <p><input id="q12" type="droptarget"/><br/>We could infer from these figures that children today spend a lot of their free time in their bedrooms.</p>
  
  

    
 
